case_description:
• Firewall logs (Mar 9 2024 10:12:00 – 10:15:00) show 4,300 outbound SYN packets from 192.168.1.42 to 93.184.216.34 on TCP ports 1‑1000;  
• Snort IDS alert “Port Scan – high rate” triggered at 10:12:05 on the same traffic;  
• NetFlow records indicate 512 distinct destination ports accessed from 192.168.1.42 during a 5‑minute window;  
• Windows Security event 4624 logs record a successful NTLM authentication on 192.168.1.42 at 09:55:00, followed by failed login at 10:10:00 from the same host;  
• Endpoint telemetry shows executable “scann.exe” launched at 10:00:12 with command-line parameters “-r 93.184.216.0/24 –p 1-1000”;  
• Email server logs capture an email body containing the string “Nmap scan report for” sent from 192.168.1.42 to mail.sysadmin@corp.local at 10:20:47.

• Source IP: 203.0.113.45 • Source port: 58412 • Destination IP range scanned: 10.0.0.0/24 for ports 20–59000 • Protocols: TCP SYN, UDP echo, ICMP echo request • Port distribution: Ports 22, 23, 53, 80, 443, 139, 445, 3389, 5900; seen 177 unique ports over 3 minutes • Timestamp: 2023‑10‑05 02:32:23 – 2023‑10‑05 02:35:10 UTC • Log sources:  
  – Firewall event ID 4201, action LOG, bandwidth 150 bytes/packet;  
  – Intrusion detection system alert ID 20231107‑A, signature “SYN scan – unknown source”;  
  – NetFlow record: source bytes 104 bytes, destination bytes 0, packet count 120;  
  – System logs: Windows Security log entry from host 10.0.0.15, event ID 4624 attempted connection to share \\10.0.0.15\share.  
• Attack pattern: rapid, overlapping SYN packets with zero ACK, followed by ICMP echo requests to same IP range; no traffic submitted TCP handshake or UDP payload. • No evidence of successful logon or file transfer; no registry changes or registry modification logs. • Threat context: indication of reconnaissance activity for lateral movement or privilege escalation within corporate LAN.
